content.text:
**[P2] Architecture concern: Device detection strategy has race condition window** (confidence: 6/10)

The device detection code (lines 170-187) runs client-side AFTER initial render:

```javascript
if (isMobile() || !isWebGLSupported()) {
  import('./components/MobileExperience').then(() => {})
} else {
  import('./components/DesktopExperience').then(() => {})
}
```

**Failure scenario**: 
1. User on fast desktop browser
2. Page renders with NO 3D content (blank screen or layout shift) during dynamic import
3. Flash of wrong content - mobile UI appears briefly before desktop loads

**Error handling**: No loading state specified. Users see broken layout during the ~100-500ms import window.

**Recommendation**: Use Next.js 14's server-side detection + dynamic imports with `ssr: false`:

```typescript
// app/page.tsx
import { headers } from 'next/headers'

const isMobileFromHeaders = () => {
  const headersList = headers()
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent') || ''
  return /Mobi|Android/i.test(userAgent)
}

export default function Home() {
  const isMobile = isMobileFromHeaders()

  return (
    <>
      {isMobile ? <MobileExperience /> : <DesktopExperience />}
    </>
  )
}
```

This prevents flash of unstyled content and eliminates client-side race condition.

Good. Zod is already a dependency for MDX typically, so this is low-cost.

**[P2] Architecture concern: WebGL context loss not handled** (confidence: 6/10)

The plan handles WebGL unsupported (no capability) but not WebGL context **loss** during use (browser tab suspend, GPU crash, driver update).

**Failure scenario**: User has portfolio open in background tab for 2 hours. Browser suspends WebGL context to save memory. User returns to tab - 3D scene is frozen/black. No error handling, no recovery.

**Recommendation**: Add R3F canvas error boundary and context loss handler:

```typescript
// components/3d/Canvas.tsx
import { Canvas } from '@react-three/fiber'
import { useErrorBoundary } from '@react-three/fiber'

export default function Scene() {
  const [gl, setGl] = useState(null)

  useEffect(() => {
    if (!gl) return

    const handleContextLoss = () => {
      // Force canvas remount
      window.location.reload()
    }

    gl.domElement.addEventListener('webglcontextlost', handleContextLoss)
    return () => {
      gl.domElement.removeEventListener('webglcontextlost', handleContextLoss)
    }
  }, [gl])

  return (
    <Canvas
      onError={(error) => {
        // Fall back to CSS-only UI
        console.error('WebGL error:', error)
        setFallback(true)
      }}
      gl={setGl}
    >
      {/* ... */}
    </Canvas>
  )
}
```

This catches crashes and degrades gracefully to CSS-only holographic effects.

Good - reusable shader components prevent duplication.

**[P2] Code quality concern: Performance monitoring code has no debounce/cooldown** (confidence: 8/10)

The performance monitoring code (lines 195-216) disables particles after 3 slow frames. But there's no re-enable mechanism. Once particles disabled, they stay disabled forever (even if device was just temporarily slow).

**Problem**: User has Chrome open in background, GC pause triggers particle disable. Forever. Site looks broken even though device is capable.

**Recommendation**: Add cooldown/re-enable logic:

```javascript
// utils/performance.js
let slowFrameCount = 0;
let disabledUntil = 0;
const DISABLE_THRESHOLD = 20;
const CONSECUTIVE_SLOW_FRAMES = 3;
const COOLDOWN_MS = 5000; // Re-enable after 5 seconds of good perf

export function measureFrameTime(delta) {
  const now = performance.now();

  if (now < disabledUntil) {
    return { shouldDisableParticles: false }; // Wait out cooldown
  }

  if (delta > DISABLE_THRESHOLD) {
    slowFrameCount++;
    if (slowFrameCount >= CONSECUTIVE_SLOW_FRAMES) {
      disabledUntil = now + COOLDOWN_MS; // Disable for 5s
      slowFrameCount = 0;
      return { shouldDisableParticles: true };
    }
  } else {
    slowFrameCount = 0;
  }
  return { shouldDisableParticles: false };
}
```

This allows particles to recover after transient slowdowns.

Good - tooling pays off quickly.

**[P3] Code quality concern: No error boundary strategy specified** (confidence: 7/10)

Plan handles WebGL errors (context loss) but not React errors in general. What if:
- Blog post MDX fails to parse
- Component throws during render
- Async data fetching fails

**Problem**: Unhandled errors crash the entire page. White screen of death. Bad for founder portfolio.

**Recommendation**: Add error boundaries at route level:

```typescript
// app/error.tsx (Next.js App Router convention)
'use client'

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string }
  reset: () => void
}) {
  return (
    <div style={{ padding: '2rem', textAlign: 'center' }}>
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
      <p style={{ fontSize: '0.9rem', color: '#666' }}>
        {error.message}
      </p>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Catches errors gracefully, shows J.A.R.V.I.S.-styled error page with retry button.

## 4. Performance Review

Analyzing the plan for N+1 queries, memory usage, and caching opportunities:

**[P2] Performance concern: No bundle splitting strategy for WebGL code** (confidence: 7/10)

Plan specifies "lazy loading, code splitting" but no specifics. R3F + Three.js is ~500KB gzipped. Loading it on mobile (where WebGL is disabled) wastes bandwidth and delays initial paint.

**Problem**: Mobile users download 500KB of WebGL code they'll never use. Initial page load slows down. Lighthouse mobile score tanks.

**Recommendation**: Implement dynamic imports for WebGL components:

```typescript
// app/page.tsx
import dynamic from 'next/dynamic'
import { Suspense } from 'react'

const DesktopExperience = dynamic(
  () => import('@/components/DesktopExperience'),
  { 
    ssr: false,
    loading: () => <div>Loading...</div>
  }
)

export default function Home() {
  const isMobile = useIsMobile()

  if (isMobile) {
    return <MobileExperience />
  }

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<LoadingSpinner />}>
      <DesktopExperience />
    </Suspense>
  )
}
```

This ensures mobile users never download the WebGL bundle. Saves ~500KB on mobile.

